1
00:01:24,292 --> 00:01:28,490
 

2
00:01:33,434 --> 00:01:35,629
 

3
00:01:40,074 --> 00:01:43,942



4
00:01:49,150 --> 00:01:53,246



5
00:01:53,321 --> 00:01:57,883
 
It's a bear! Look at that!

6
00:01:57,959 --> 00:02:00,393
 
 

7
00:02:00,461 --> 00:02:03,726
He's a big one.
You get back!

8
00:02:03,798 --> 00:02:07,734
 

9
00:02:07,802 --> 00:02:11,898
 
  Come back here!

10
00:02:14,909 --> 00:02:19,243
 

11
00:02:31,959 --> 00:02:34,257
[Wild Barking,
Ferocious Growling]

12
00:02:34,328 --> 00:02:37,229
 
Get back!

13
00:02:40,535 --> 00:02:43,333
 

14
00:02:43,404 --> 00:02:45,338
Gracie.

15
00:02:53,548 --> 00:02:57,416
He was one of my bravest--
scars from 14 battles if a one.

16
00:02:57,485 --> 00:03:00,750
I see 'em.
Father was a huntin'hound.

17
00:03:00,822 --> 00:03:03,313
Mother, a German dog. Tan.

18
00:03:03,391 --> 00:03:05,325
Might live,
you doctor it.

19
00:03:05,393 --> 00:03:08,920
Never get the courage back.
I know dogs.

20
00:03:08,996 --> 00:03:11,829
 

21
00:03:11,899 --> 00:03:15,391
He's mangled her innards!
Can't digest bread.

22
00:03:15,470 --> 00:03:17,597
Can chew it anyway.

23
00:03:19,407 --> 00:03:22,808
  Come away, Rebecca. They're
gonna have to send him up to the fields.

24
00:03:22,877 --> 00:03:26,472
  Why they have to do that?
'Cause he can't walk anymore.

25
00:03:32,220 --> 00:03:34,211
 

26
00:03:34,288 --> 00:03:37,086
Come on.
Come on.

27
00:03:37,158 --> 00:03:40,093
 

28
00:03:42,163 --> 00:03:45,599
 
In the North Carolina mountains...

29
00:03:45,666 --> 00:03:49,966
the early settlers traveled the roads,
taKing their stock down to the market...

30
00:03:50,037 --> 00:03:55,441
and trekking back up again with supplies
and new stock for the months ahead.

31
00:03:57,345 --> 00:04:01,873
Among them was a man
named August King.

32
00:04:01,949 --> 00:04:05,282
He had been waiting his turn
most ofhis life...

33
00:04:05,353 --> 00:04:09,380
never doing anything much
different from one day to the next.

34
00:04:10,458 --> 00:04:13,689
He was alone on his journey...

35
00:04:13,761 --> 00:04:16,559
walking at his own gait,
slow and steady...

36
00:04:16,631 --> 00:04:19,191
making his way home.
 

37
00:04:19,267 --> 00:04:21,201
M-m-moo.

38
00:04:22,436 --> 00:04:24,836
Wasn't after you,
that old bear.

39
00:04:24,906 --> 00:04:27,932
 
Wasn't after anybody.

40
00:04:31,879 --> 00:04:33,813
 

41
00:04:48,329 --> 00:04:50,263
 

42
00:05:15,656 --> 00:05:18,090
 

43
00:05:22,330 --> 00:05:25,925
It's all right.
 

44
00:05:27,668 --> 00:05:30,603
Lost?

45
00:05:30,671 --> 00:05:32,866
You want to follow
this creek...

46
00:05:33,941 --> 00:05:36,409
till you get to the bridge
by the inn.

47
00:05:38,145 --> 00:05:40,875
That's north.

48
00:05:40,948 --> 00:05:43,109
Will you help me?

49
00:05:43,184 --> 00:05:47,382
Oh, no. Can't do that.

50
00:05:47,455 --> 00:05:49,389
Against the law.

51
00:05:51,492 --> 00:05:54,984
 
  Did you hit him?

52
00:05:55,062 --> 00:05:59,294
  Surely did. Fattest turkey
ever seen the light of day!

53
00:06:09,210 --> 00:06:12,179
  Had men tracking them
two days near Pride...

54
00:06:12,246 --> 00:06:14,180
then they lost them.

55
00:06:14,248 --> 00:06:16,978
Fellow says he saw the boy drinking in
the creek down from the bridge a piece.

56
00:06:17,051 --> 00:06:18,985
Heading north, they'll be.

57
00:06:19,053 --> 00:06:21,681
  Keeping close to the road,
so as not to lose themselves.

58
00:06:21,756 --> 00:06:25,021
  Night. Be movin'at night
with their cat's eyes.

59
00:06:25,092 --> 00:06:27,720
See better in the dark
than they do in the day.

60
00:06:29,063 --> 00:06:32,624
 
Well, August King!

61
00:06:32,700 --> 00:06:35,430
I see you made it
another year.

62
00:06:35,503 --> 00:06:40,202
Sorry about your wife.
A sad loss.

63
00:06:40,274 --> 00:06:43,641
I brought the money for your loan.

64
00:06:43,711 --> 00:06:47,044
  Old Bolt gonna be
cleanest he ever been since he was born.

65
00:06:47,114 --> 00:06:50,777
You paid off a valuable
farm now, August.

66
00:06:50,851 --> 00:06:53,479
How much you give me for it?
You sell it?

67
00:06:53,554 --> 00:06:56,682
No. I'm there for life. Just
wonder what it's worth is all.

68
00:06:56,757 --> 00:06:59,089
No river bottomland,
that right?

69
00:06:59,160 --> 00:07:02,323
No. It's steep.
The rich ones won't buy steep.

70
00:07:02,396 --> 00:07:06,093
You'd think since they can
afford slaves to work it--

71
00:07:06,167 --> 00:07:08,727
Don't allow slaves,
the community I live in.

72
00:07:08,803 --> 00:07:12,330
Olaf Singletary lost
two slaves a few days ago.

73
00:07:12,406 --> 00:07:14,533
A boy and a girl.

74
00:07:14,608 --> 00:07:17,304
Must be the wealthiest man
in the mountains, don't you agree?

75
00:07:17,378 --> 00:07:20,643
Thought you were.

76
00:07:20,715 --> 00:07:23,684
 
So how old was the girl?

77
00:07:25,286 --> 00:07:27,220
Did you see her?

78
00:07:30,291 --> 00:07:33,852
I'll be needin' supplies...
and the deed to my land.

79
00:07:33,928 --> 00:07:37,762
The deed to your land!
Yes, sir.

80
00:07:37,832 --> 00:07:39,766
Harristown, Harristown.

81
00:07:39,834 --> 00:07:42,132
That's under"H."

82
00:07:43,504 --> 00:07:46,530
Got it right here.

83
00:07:52,013 --> 00:07:54,504
You might mark it paid.

84
00:08:01,522 --> 00:08:03,456
Be best to date it.

85
00:08:07,161 --> 00:08:10,324
Twenty-seven, April...

86
00:08:10,398 --> 00:08:13,799
1815.

87
00:08:13,868 --> 00:08:16,598
§  

88
00:08:22,143 --> 00:08:25,078
 

89
00:08:40,161 --> 00:08:43,062
§  

90
00:09:06,520 --> 00:09:10,183
§ [Solo Flute Begins
Playing A Gig]

91
00:09:13,494 --> 00:09:17,021
Who's this long face?
Wanna dance with me?

92
00:09:17,098 --> 00:09:19,032
Whoo. I'm no dancer.

93
00:09:19,100 --> 00:09:23,469
Then I'll teach you.
About done from the trail.

94
00:09:24,705 --> 00:09:26,639
Come on.

95
00:09:27,875 --> 00:09:29,809
What's wrong?

96
00:09:31,479 --> 00:09:35,916
It ain't so bad, is it, that you
can't manage a smile for a girl?

97
00:09:35,983 --> 00:09:37,917
I'm sorry.

98
00:09:45,626 --> 00:09:48,117
I want that girl back!

99
00:09:48,195 --> 00:09:52,655
You men find her.
I'll pay for your time.

100
00:09:52,733 --> 00:09:55,327
Let your dogs find her.

101
00:09:55,402 --> 00:09:59,566
It's against the law
to run off like she's done.

102
00:09:59,640 --> 00:10:02,006
What you offerin', Olaf,
for the girl?

103
00:10:02,076 --> 00:10:04,306
Ten acres of land
alongside the river.

104
00:10:04,378 --> 00:10:07,370
Flood?
No, it won't flood.

105
00:10:07,448 --> 00:10:10,110
My man here'll tell you.

106
00:10:10,184 --> 00:10:14,848
Olaf, you're wantin' us to release our
dogs, do you a favor-- and it's trouble.

107
00:10:14,922 --> 00:10:17,186
Hurts my conscience, too...

108
00:10:17,258 --> 00:10:20,250
to set dogs on people.

109
00:10:20,327 --> 00:10:23,387
You want slaves;
you can tend to 'em.

110
00:10:23,464 --> 00:10:26,262
Five acres more.

111
00:10:26,333 --> 00:10:28,767
That enough on behalf
of your conscience?

112
00:10:28,836 --> 00:10:33,773
And one more thing! We'll have
that Maryland horse you ride.

113
00:10:33,841 --> 00:10:38,005
And the saddle.
All right.

114
00:10:38,078 --> 00:10:41,570
  What you offerin'
for that Sims? That boy runaway?

115
00:10:41,649 --> 00:10:44,413
A grand $70 reward for the man
and be damned!

116
00:10:44,485 --> 00:10:47,613
Now I want men watchin'
every river crossin'...

117
00:10:47,688 --> 00:10:50,486
and any man found helpin'them
is a dead man.

118
00:10:50,558 --> 00:10:53,288
 

119
00:10:58,265 --> 00:11:00,199
 

120
00:11:10,844 --> 00:11:12,778
 

121
00:11:21,388 --> 00:11:24,323
 

122
00:11:26,227 --> 00:11:30,527
 
Need sugar too.

123
00:11:42,409 --> 00:11:45,708
Looks like you did pretty
well for yourself at market.

124
00:11:45,779 --> 00:11:48,145
I bought this cow and geese.

125
00:11:48,215 --> 00:11:50,206
The cow at home's old.

126
00:11:50,284 --> 00:11:53,014
Only chickens at my place.

127
00:11:53,087 --> 00:11:55,578
Bought the young boar
to improve my drove.

128
00:11:55,656 --> 00:11:59,023
Managed to make improvements
just about every year.

129
00:11:59,093 --> 00:12:03,359
How far away you live?
About three days if I hurry.

130
00:12:03,430 --> 00:12:05,364
Might not hurry.

131
00:12:09,169 --> 00:12:11,660
 
Have they caught Olaf's runaways yet?

132
00:12:11,739 --> 00:12:13,673
 
Don't know.

133
00:12:13,741 --> 00:12:16,301
  That rich man's
offerin' a horse for the girl!

134
00:12:16,377 --> 00:12:19,278
Seems like he'll do most
anything to get her back.

135
00:12:19,346 --> 00:12:23,976
I have ideas about offerin'
a horse for a human.

136
00:12:24,051 --> 00:12:26,485
 

137
00:12:26,553 --> 00:12:28,612
Set dogs on 'em too.

138
00:12:38,299 --> 00:12:40,733
 

139
00:12:40,801 --> 00:12:44,168
 

140
00:12:47,541 --> 00:12:50,533
Get off there. Get down!
That's enough.

141
00:12:50,611 --> 00:12:53,375
She must have been in heat!
 

142
00:12:53,447 --> 00:12:55,677
She never wore that.

143
00:12:55,749 --> 00:12:59,378
That's the boy's shirt.
Well, what does she smell like, Olaf?

144
00:12:59,453 --> 00:13:01,387
That's not hers.
I told you.

145
00:13:01,455 --> 00:13:04,390
Can we use her a little bit
on the way in, Olaf?

146
00:13:04,458 --> 00:13:06,392
 

147
00:13:09,997 --> 00:13:12,329
I tell you I want her
unsullied.

148
00:13:12,399 --> 00:13:14,924
What if she asks for it, Olaf?

149
00:13:15,002 --> 00:13:17,266
Then let her suck your finger!
 

150
00:13:22,743 --> 00:13:25,177
I demand her back unsullied.

151
00:13:34,455 --> 00:13:36,980
§ There §

152
00:13:37,057 --> 00:13:41,153
§ Was an old man
lived up on a hill §

153
00:13:41,228 --> 00:13:44,095
§  

154
00:13:44,164 --> 00:13:50,034
§ A-singin' hi-di
diddly-l-fi hee §

155
00:13:50,104 --> 00:13:53,904
§ Diddle-l, diddle-l-day §

156
00:13:54,975 --> 00:13:58,103
§ When he got her down
'bout half a road §

157
00:13:58,178 --> 00:14:01,909
§ Old, old lady
she's a hell of a load §

158
00:14:01,982 --> 00:14:06,385
§ Singin'hi-diddle-l
diddle-l-fi hee §

159
00:14:06,453 --> 00:14:08,387
 

160
00:14:08,455 --> 00:14:10,889
§ A-diddle-l, diddle-l-day §

161
00:14:10,958 --> 00:14:12,892
 

162
00:14:15,562 --> 00:14:17,689
Come here.

163
00:14:20,367 --> 00:14:22,301
Pretty cow.

164
00:14:22,369 --> 00:14:24,929
 

165
00:14:38,318 --> 00:14:40,252
 

166
00:14:54,368 --> 00:14:56,302
Hey, August!

167
00:15:02,543 --> 00:15:05,808
What you been doin' in there, August?
What you think?

168
00:15:05,879 --> 00:15:10,145
 
Don't I smell corn bread?

169
00:15:13,420 --> 00:15:15,684
 

170
00:15:15,756 --> 00:15:18,190
Most everyone on the road
wants that bounty now.

171
00:15:18,258 --> 00:15:20,954
 
Sounds like they're on a scent.

172
00:15:21,028 --> 00:15:23,588
He's headin' up
through the woods towards here.

173
00:15:23,664 --> 00:15:25,928
You better put that pig
in your cart!

174
00:15:25,999 --> 00:15:27,899
 

175
00:15:33,907 --> 00:15:37,638
 

176
00:15:39,646 --> 00:15:41,876
What are they
tearin'up, August?

177
00:15:41,949 --> 00:15:45,578
That corn bread too?
I think so!

178
00:15:47,354 --> 00:15:50,653
What you got there,
damn it?

179
00:15:50,724 --> 00:15:53,887
Where'd they go?
Where in the hell did they get to?

180
00:15:53,961 --> 00:15:57,897
Now, these dogs
struck a trail. Come on!

181
00:16:01,268 --> 00:16:04,726
Corn bread here's still warm.

182
00:16:04,805 --> 00:16:07,933
Bread them dogs is eatin'
warm too.

183
00:16:20,020 --> 00:16:22,580
 

184
00:16:24,157 --> 00:16:30,027
You want to make camp with us?
A few more stretches and curves.

185
00:16:30,097 --> 00:16:32,861
Need to ask your name
and where you're from.

186
00:16:32,933 --> 00:16:37,131
I'm August King.
The one whose woman drew the pictures?

187
00:16:37,204 --> 00:16:39,536
My sister said she was
the best artist in the country.

188
00:16:39,606 --> 00:16:43,235
She could draw a picture faster
than a clown could fall over.

189
00:16:43,310 --> 00:16:45,471
She'd draw me and--

190
00:16:45,546 --> 00:16:49,209
Draw me walkin' down the path.

191
00:16:49,283 --> 00:16:51,274
She used pages
right from the Bible.

192
00:16:51,351 --> 00:16:53,376
Why, that's unholy.

193
00:16:53,453 --> 00:16:55,819
Pages from the Bible unholy?

194
00:16:55,889 --> 00:17:00,849
To draw on them.
She used the ones she didn't care for.

195
00:17:00,928 --> 00:17:05,558
She kept Psalms. Used about half
the book of Exodus 'fore she died.

196
00:17:05,632 --> 00:17:10,296
I always wanted her to do
Emily and Alice here... in colors.

197
00:17:12,105 --> 00:17:15,506
Well, you can't travel
in the dark!

198
00:17:15,576 --> 00:17:17,510
 

199
00:17:20,247 --> 00:17:22,181
Did I offend him?

200
00:17:22,249 --> 00:17:24,683
Reminded him of his wife
too often, I imagine.

201
00:17:24,751 --> 00:17:28,482
Hope I don't die strange
as she did.

202
00:17:54,281 --> 00:17:58,012
 

203
00:17:59,086 --> 00:18:01,884
 

204
00:18:15,469 --> 00:18:17,494
What you stop for?

205
00:18:19,773 --> 00:18:22,367
Three reports
of seein' Sims.

206
00:18:23,443 --> 00:18:26,537
Tomorrow we'll--
we'll catch him.

207
00:18:31,251 --> 00:18:34,652
Lord knows, we'll--
we'll find her too.

208
00:18:34,721 --> 00:18:37,849
Why do you need to find her?

209
00:18:37,924 --> 00:18:41,189
You have so many slaves.

210
00:18:43,463 --> 00:18:47,661
She was like a ray of--
a ray of light to me.

211
00:18:49,269 --> 00:18:51,669
It was a cool night.

212
00:18:53,607 --> 00:18:55,541
When I woke...

213
00:18:57,411 --> 00:19:00,073
I was holdin' a pillow.

214
00:19:00,147 --> 00:19:03,082
Her-- She was gone.

215
00:19:05,152 --> 00:19:07,882
She's the one that's
supposed to...

216
00:19:07,954 --> 00:19:10,980
tend the fire.

217
00:19:13,827 --> 00:19:15,761
 

218
00:19:17,264 --> 00:19:19,198
Why you do that?
 

219
00:19:19,266 --> 00:19:23,726
Callin' her back,
she near enough to hear it.

220
00:19:23,804 --> 00:19:27,501
World of rumors about...

221
00:19:27,574 --> 00:19:31,135
Africans havin' more than...

222
00:19:31,211 --> 00:19:33,270
five fingers and toes.

223
00:19:33,346 --> 00:19:37,112
You ever hear that?
I heard it's so.

224
00:19:37,184 --> 00:19:40,449
It's not my observation.

225
00:19:43,156 --> 00:19:45,522
She near?

226
00:19:50,063 --> 00:19:51,997
I'll be goin'.

227
00:20:19,559 --> 00:20:22,050
 

228
00:20:26,133 --> 00:20:28,601
 

229
00:20:29,669 --> 00:20:32,502
 

230
00:20:49,055 --> 00:20:53,014
 

231
00:21:03,637 --> 00:21:05,935
What you want here?

232
00:21:07,574 --> 00:21:09,508
I give you this.
You help me.

233
00:21:09,576 --> 00:21:12,170
What you been doin'
followin' me?

234
00:21:13,914 --> 00:21:17,611
You see me yesterday
and don't tell nobody.

235
00:21:18,685 --> 00:21:20,983
Where's the boy
you run off with?

236
00:21:21,054 --> 00:21:23,648
We lost each other.

237
00:21:23,723 --> 00:21:25,657
Won't come
outta those bushes?

238
00:21:30,030 --> 00:21:32,590
See, it's a watch.

239
00:21:32,666 --> 00:21:36,363
Silver. For you,
if you help me.

240
00:21:36,436 --> 00:21:39,234
Belongs to Olaf Singletary.

241
00:21:41,074 --> 00:21:43,008
He give it me.

242
00:21:44,878 --> 00:21:46,812
Stolen property.

243
00:21:49,249 --> 00:21:51,183
He give it me.

244
00:21:55,755 --> 00:21:57,689
 

245
00:22:02,229 --> 00:22:05,289
I try all day not to die.

246
00:22:05,365 --> 00:22:08,027
I ate leaves this mornin'.

247
00:22:08,101 --> 00:22:10,296
They went through me
like a fire.

248
00:22:25,619 --> 00:22:27,553
No one ever teach you
how to chew?

249
00:22:30,357 --> 00:22:33,918
No one teach me
how to starve.

250
00:22:36,029 --> 00:22:39,396
Your fat owner's camped
back thataway. I can show you.

251
00:22:39,466 --> 00:22:43,197
You had enough freedom now.
What's he doin'?

252
00:22:43,270 --> 00:22:47,366
Take you back in a carriage, I expect.
Seems so anxious to have you.

253
00:22:47,440 --> 00:22:49,431
What's he doin'?
I asked you.

254
00:22:51,378 --> 00:22:54,142
Well, he's beatin' on a pan.

255
00:22:57,050 --> 00:22:59,109
There ain't nothin' funny
about him.

256
00:23:04,891 --> 00:23:08,292
Finish that.
I'll get you some milk.

257
00:23:08,361 --> 00:23:10,659
Then you go on your way.

258
00:23:14,567 --> 00:23:17,001
 

259
00:23:33,753 --> 00:23:37,621
 
  Hey.

260
00:23:39,359 --> 00:23:41,293
Hey.

261
00:23:46,933 --> 00:23:48,867
 
Hey.

262
00:23:49,936 --> 00:23:54,873
 

263
00:24:13,026 --> 00:24:15,620
 

264
00:24:18,231 --> 00:24:20,165
Damn!

265
00:24:20,233 --> 00:24:23,361
I don't allow men
any chance with me.

266
00:24:23,436 --> 00:24:26,234
I just wakin' you up...
and get rid of you.

267
00:24:29,709 --> 00:24:31,904
Man need a rope
to get near you.

268
00:24:31,978 --> 00:24:36,108
Come on. Move on outta here...

269
00:24:36,182 --> 00:24:38,810
'fore someone finds you.

270
00:24:40,453 --> 00:24:42,387
 
Come on.

271
00:24:54,567 --> 00:24:57,058
 

272
00:24:59,706 --> 00:25:02,675
It's my watch
to give anyways.

273
00:25:12,652 --> 00:25:15,086
You sleep in that cart
till mornin'.

274
00:25:17,123 --> 00:25:19,523
Then you're gone.

275
00:25:42,882 --> 00:25:47,785
 

276
00:25:51,791 --> 00:25:53,725
 

277
00:26:18,585 --> 00:26:20,985
 

278
00:26:21,054 --> 00:26:22,988
 

279
00:26:25,125 --> 00:26:27,423
 

280
00:26:37,170 --> 00:26:40,333
Here I am, lonely, my son's
trailin' slow with my cattle...

281
00:26:40,406 --> 00:26:44,399
and I come upon a friend
from my own community.

282
00:26:44,477 --> 00:26:47,935
Been wantin' coffee all mornin'
and not had ary a drop.

283
00:26:55,054 --> 00:26:57,784
Mmm. Oh, my, how glad
I am to meet you.

284
00:26:57,857 --> 00:27:00,655
How are you, August?
Tell me.

285
00:27:00,727 --> 00:27:03,389
Wantin' to be on my way.
That's how I am.

286
00:27:03,463 --> 00:27:08,127
And you livin' alone too. It's not
recommended for a man to live alone.

287
00:27:08,201 --> 00:27:11,637
Well, I'll have a solution
for that one of these days now.

288
00:27:11,704 --> 00:27:15,367
What do you do by yourself
to distract your thoughts?

289
00:27:15,441 --> 00:27:18,239
I read the Bible.
 

290
00:27:18,311 --> 00:27:20,711
 
Here they are.

291
00:27:20,780 --> 00:27:23,214
I'll be goin' now, Fisher.

292
00:27:25,652 --> 00:27:29,611
August? You had
a woman here last night.

293
00:27:31,491 --> 00:27:34,858
You had a woman here
last night. I allow!

294
00:27:34,928 --> 00:27:38,386
Farmer and his wife is all.
Yeah, they were by.

295
00:27:41,100 --> 00:27:44,934
Small feet. Injured feet.

296
00:27:45,004 --> 00:27:47,199
Woman tracks.

297
00:27:47,273 --> 00:27:50,868
Had female company, August did!
 

298
00:27:50,944 --> 00:27:54,607
And you always so proper,
August.

299
00:27:54,681 --> 00:27:56,842
Ah, she's probably nigh.

300
00:27:56,916 --> 00:28:00,977
Might be in them bushes, peeing.
 

301
00:28:01,054 --> 00:28:03,079
[Cattle Bawling,
Cart Rattling]

302
00:28:03,156 --> 00:28:08,025
Hey, August! You left
your coffee pot!

303
00:28:08,094 --> 00:28:11,188
 
Move on, move on. Come on, there!

304
00:28:19,005 --> 00:28:22,236
 

305
00:28:22,308 --> 00:28:25,004
 
Get along. Get around!

306
00:28:25,078 --> 00:28:28,912
  Hello, mister!
Look at the piggie under the cart.

307
00:28:28,982 --> 00:28:32,918
  Slow down, damn it!
You're gonna hit the sheep!

308
00:28:34,354 --> 00:28:36,982
Get out! Go on, sheep!

309
00:28:37,056 --> 00:28:41,550
 

310
00:28:41,628 --> 00:28:44,153
 
That man's gone crazy!

311
00:28:44,230 --> 00:28:46,721
Come on! Come on,
stay outta there.

312
00:28:46,799 --> 00:28:50,667
Louise, get back up there
and head 'em off.

313
00:28:54,240 --> 00:28:56,674
 

314
00:29:00,079 --> 00:29:04,948
I'm not one for big adventures. I don't
need excitement first thing a mornin'.

315
00:29:05,018 --> 00:29:08,818
What they do to you if you help me?
I'm not gonna find out.

316
00:29:11,524 --> 00:29:13,458
I never made the laws.

317
00:29:13,526 --> 00:29:15,494
I'm simply a one-man farmer.

318
00:29:17,330 --> 00:29:20,527
He gone and burned my shoes
after I runs away first time.

319
00:29:20,600 --> 00:29:23,501
Don't bite me.

320
00:29:34,614 --> 00:29:36,548
 

321
00:29:41,254 --> 00:29:45,020
 
 

322
00:29:45,091 --> 00:29:47,025
It's gonna heal 'em.

323
00:29:47,093 --> 00:29:49,061
 

324
00:29:51,130 --> 00:29:53,064
Lay your hands.

325
00:29:54,734 --> 00:29:56,702
Drink that down.

326
00:29:58,137 --> 00:30:00,469
 

327
00:30:03,376 --> 00:30:06,209
Ever had peach brandy?

328
00:30:06,279 --> 00:30:10,648
There ain't no peaches in that.

329
00:30:10,717 --> 00:30:14,676
 

330
00:30:34,540 --> 00:30:38,135
I can be so small that nobody
ever gonna see me in your cart.

331
00:30:43,349 --> 00:30:46,409
Stop scratchin'.

332
00:30:46,486 --> 00:30:49,512
But it itches, and when
I itch I can't stop.

333
00:30:51,290 --> 00:30:53,622
Well, a woman's thighs
start a man thinkin'.

334
00:30:55,528 --> 00:30:57,519
How old are you, anyway?

335
00:30:57,597 --> 00:30:59,531
Seventeen.

336
00:31:01,567 --> 00:31:05,298
 
Do you have any modesty?

337
00:31:05,371 --> 00:31:07,566
Don't you be talkin'
to me like that.

338
00:31:07,640 --> 00:31:11,406
Well, don't you scratch
so much.

339
00:31:16,749 --> 00:31:20,708
Anyone finds you, I'm gonna say
I'm takin' you in.

340
00:31:30,663 --> 00:31:32,654
 

341
00:31:35,968 --> 00:31:37,993
 
Come on, boy. Come on.

342
00:31:38,070 --> 00:31:43,030
What is it, Rusty?
 

343
00:31:44,577 --> 00:31:49,446
 
 

344
00:32:02,161 --> 00:32:04,095
If you won't tell.

345
00:32:09,769 --> 00:32:12,397
It's no need, mister.

346
00:32:12,472 --> 00:32:15,134
But you better not let
Mama and Papa see her.

347
00:32:19,378 --> 00:32:21,312
She ain't hungry, is she?

348
00:32:22,682 --> 00:32:24,616
I think she'd like that.

349
00:32:33,192 --> 00:32:37,026
I ate my apple.

350
00:32:37,096 --> 00:32:39,030
They're lookin' for her
everywhere.

351
00:32:39,098 --> 00:32:42,556
Daniel! Henry!
What you doin'back there?

352
00:32:42,635 --> 00:32:44,933
Come on, Rusty. Come on.
We're waitin'on you!

353
00:32:45,004 --> 00:32:48,303
 

354
00:32:48,374 --> 00:32:50,569
Sorry, Papa.
We saw bear tracks.

355
00:32:50,643 --> 00:32:53,942
A real big one!
What you doin' talkin' to that man?

356
00:33:04,457 --> 00:33:07,551
 

357
00:33:12,298 --> 00:33:15,631
 
Hey!

358
00:33:15,701 --> 00:33:18,226
Them boys tell?

359
00:33:18,304 --> 00:33:20,704
I don't believe so.

360
00:33:20,773 --> 00:33:23,435
I didn't want you
gettin' in trouble.

361
00:33:23,509 --> 00:33:26,069
Why you went?
Yeah.

362
00:33:27,179 --> 00:33:30,876
 
Never told me your name.

363
00:33:32,785 --> 00:33:37,381
Williamsburg.
He called me after a town.

364
00:33:37,456 --> 00:33:39,754
Oh, my Lord.

365
00:33:39,825 --> 00:33:42,794
You're not supposed
to be called William...

366
00:33:42,862 --> 00:33:44,796
much less"Burg."

367
00:33:47,500 --> 00:33:49,525
Whoa.

368
00:33:49,602 --> 00:33:54,539
I is called Annalees
by most everybody. Or Anna.

369
00:33:54,607 --> 00:33:58,566
You like Annalees?
It's an improvement.

370
00:34:00,713 --> 00:34:03,375
  Come on, Crosby!
Best get in.

371
00:34:06,485 --> 00:34:08,419
 

372
00:34:14,360 --> 00:34:16,624
Get down.
Lie down.

373
00:34:35,748 --> 00:34:40,048
More rain comin', looks like.
Right.

374
00:34:47,226 --> 00:34:49,820
 
So how are you, August?

375
00:34:49,895 --> 00:34:53,695
Just common. You all right?
I'll do.

376
00:34:53,766 --> 00:34:57,634
  Take him out!
He can't breathe air.

377
00:34:57,703 --> 00:34:59,694
 
Yes, he can. He's gettin'too hot.

378
00:34:59,772 --> 00:35:04,368
Any slave owners come by?
One a while back.

379
00:35:04,443 --> 00:35:07,503
That fat fella?
They all fat.

380
00:35:07,580 --> 00:35:11,175
Yeah. All right.
  I got slime all over my dress!

381
00:35:12,752 --> 00:35:17,155
Say, August, that sure is a pretty cow
you bought at the market!

382
00:35:17,223 --> 00:35:21,455
Isn't she? Promisin' my wife
for years to buy a new one.

383
00:35:22,895 --> 00:35:26,831
 

384
00:35:32,638 --> 00:35:35,038
 
Keep down.

385
00:35:35,107 --> 00:35:38,838
I am keepin' down.
Could be anyone lookin' on.

386
00:35:40,312 --> 00:35:44,214
Them mountains,
they cut my feet wide open.

387
00:35:44,283 --> 00:35:47,081
You cut them open,
blood flows out too.

388
00:35:47,153 --> 00:35:50,554
Life's as bad as these
mountains are.

389
00:35:50,623 --> 00:35:53,023
The blood is the water,
you-all tellin' me?

390
00:35:53,092 --> 00:35:56,391
Every mountain has a life of its own.
 

391
00:35:56,462 --> 00:36:00,922
Sarah used to say,
"If it's alive, how do you kill it?"

392
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:03,525
Who's Sarah?

393
00:36:03,602 --> 00:36:06,435
My wife.

394
00:36:06,505 --> 00:36:08,564
And I'd say,
"Well, you can't kill it."

395
00:36:08,641 --> 00:36:12,099
And she'd say,"lf you can't kill it,
how much alive is it?"

396
00:36:12,178 --> 00:36:14,874
That's what she'd say.
 

397
00:36:14,947 --> 00:36:18,246
Hey. Whoa.
Hold it.

398
00:36:18,317 --> 00:36:20,808
What's the matter?

399
00:36:20,886 --> 00:36:22,854
 
You're all tangled up.

400
00:36:22,922 --> 00:36:24,856
 

401
00:36:28,327 --> 00:36:31,888
She waitin' for you at home?
Your wife?

402
00:36:33,365 --> 00:36:36,596
Sarah passed away.
How she die?

403
00:36:36,669 --> 00:36:39,536
It's bad to ask.

404
00:36:39,605 --> 00:36:42,904
She lost her footin'...
on a ridge above our house.

405
00:36:42,975 --> 00:36:44,966
They got loose stones there.

406
00:36:47,246 --> 00:36:49,737
God must've caught her, August.

407
00:36:49,815 --> 00:36:52,283
He caught her in his hand.

408
00:36:54,887 --> 00:36:56,821
 
 

409
00:37:00,326 --> 00:37:02,260
 

410
00:37:06,632 --> 00:37:09,066
 

411
00:37:26,685 --> 00:37:30,018
  § There was
an old man lived over the hill §

412
00:37:30,089 --> 00:37:32,853
§ Ifhe ain't dead
he's livin'there still §

413
00:37:32,925 --> 00:37:36,019
§ Singin'hi diddle-l
diddle-l-fi §

414
00:37:36,095 --> 00:37:38,461
§ A-diddle-I diddle-l-day §

415
00:37:38,531 --> 00:37:42,331
§ Well, the devil he comes
to steal one day §

416
00:37:42,401 --> 00:37:44,767
§ Say your old wife
gonna take her away §

417
00:37:44,837 --> 00:37:47,533
§ Singin' hi diddle-l
diddle-l-fi §

418
00:37:47,606 --> 00:37:52,669
  § Diddle-l-day hee
diddly-I diddly-I day §

419
00:37:52,745 --> 00:37:56,875
  § And sang clickety-clack §
§  

420
00:37:56,949 --> 00:37:59,645
§ On his back §

421
00:37:59,718 --> 00:38:02,482
§ And diddle-I diddle-l-fi §

422
00:38:02,555 --> 00:38:04,819
Ohh!

423
00:38:26,478 --> 00:38:28,912
 

424
00:38:30,149 --> 00:38:32,982
  Anybody gonna
have that outhouse--

425
00:38:33,052 --> 00:38:35,020
That's my Aunt Louise
with my mama.

426
00:38:35,087 --> 00:38:40,457
 
Maybe they think I'm dead.

427
00:38:51,937 --> 00:38:54,906
Better wait a goodly
while till they get on.

428
00:38:54,974 --> 00:38:57,807
Which one of you called out
to him, huh?

429
00:38:57,877 --> 00:39:00,971
You's gonna honk me
right in his lap.

430
00:39:01,046 --> 00:39:03,947
Win me that horse of his.

431
00:39:08,254 --> 00:39:10,620
You thinkin' of it?

432
00:39:25,871 --> 00:39:29,068
Must want you bad,
offerin' land.

433
00:39:31,210 --> 00:39:33,144
I was his house servant.

434
00:39:34,246 --> 00:39:36,180
That different
from a field hand?

435
00:39:38,317 --> 00:39:41,047
Means I wait on him
night and day.

436
00:39:42,121 --> 00:39:44,612
He want his tea.

437
00:39:44,690 --> 00:39:46,988
He want his toast buttered.

438
00:39:47,059 --> 00:39:49,527
He want his fire made.

439
00:39:49,595 --> 00:39:52,189
He want his garden hoed.

440
00:39:52,264 --> 00:39:56,633
He want quiet in his house.
He want his shirt washed.

441
00:39:59,672 --> 00:40:03,073
He's strong as an ox too.

442
00:40:07,379 --> 00:40:11,338
Had a roof over your head.
Why you run away?

443
00:40:14,787 --> 00:40:17,517
Keep him from takin' my soul.

444
00:40:22,094 --> 00:40:24,528
 

445
00:40:26,665 --> 00:40:30,692
You know this cow makes milk
out of fallen leaves? It's a miracle.

446
00:40:30,769 --> 00:40:32,703
Queen of cows.

447
00:40:34,440 --> 00:40:36,374
And you is August King.

448
00:40:38,110 --> 00:40:40,044
Yeah.

449
00:40:42,247 --> 00:40:45,978
 

450
00:40:50,255 --> 00:40:50,456
 

451
00:40:50,456 --> 00:40:53,016
 

452
00:41:00,366 --> 00:41:03,824
I never knew a man
named after a month before.

453
00:41:03,902 --> 00:41:07,702
You get women named June.

454
00:41:07,773 --> 00:41:10,105
April.

455
00:41:10,175 --> 00:41:12,939
May. I knew two Mays.
May?

456
00:41:13,012 --> 00:41:14,946
Uh-huh.

457
00:41:17,149 --> 00:41:21,449
July. July King.

458
00:41:21,520 --> 00:41:23,954
August.

459
00:41:24,023 --> 00:41:28,119
l'se called November.
My name is November King.

460
00:41:28,193 --> 00:41:31,424
November King.
What the hell you talkin' about?

461
00:41:31,497 --> 00:41:34,591
 
October King!

462
00:41:34,666 --> 00:41:37,829
 
August King!

463
00:41:37,903 --> 00:41:40,963
 
  The devil's back on us!

464
00:41:41,040 --> 00:41:44,532
 
There he goes! He ran into the house!

465
00:41:49,448 --> 00:41:53,350
Get around the side!
Plug them holes!

466
00:41:56,789 --> 00:42:00,247
Did you see him? Did he run through?
Who you talkin'about?

467
00:42:00,325 --> 00:42:05,353
The runaway, damn it! Must still
be inside. Boys, let them dogs go.

468
00:42:05,431 --> 00:42:07,524
Sure you seen him?
Well, I seen somethin' move!

469
00:42:09,635 --> 00:42:11,569
Whoa.

470
00:42:18,677 --> 00:42:21,703
They didn't find Sims,
did they?

471
00:42:21,780 --> 00:42:23,714
Shadow's all they saw.

472
00:42:26,552 --> 00:42:28,850
They shootin' at him.

473
00:42:30,422 --> 00:42:32,356
Shadows.

474
00:42:33,525 --> 00:42:35,459
They shoot at me?

475
00:42:35,527 --> 00:42:37,461
Can't shoot
what they can't find.

476
00:42:40,265 --> 00:42:43,098
I know what they do to me,
all those men.

477
00:42:43,168 --> 00:42:47,969
I tell you, I jump from off
a cliff'fore they catch me.

478
00:43:01,253 --> 00:43:04,745
 

479
00:43:23,909 --> 00:43:29,313
Ah, there you are.
Must've ridden past you earlier on.

480
00:43:29,381 --> 00:43:32,373
I'm told you caught your girl.
Not yet.

481
00:43:32,451 --> 00:43:34,385
Know where she is, do you?

482
00:43:34,453 --> 00:43:36,478
Back thataway,
I imagine.

483
00:43:39,091 --> 00:43:42,151
Lanky farmer named Fisher.
First man at my camp this morning.

484
00:43:42,227 --> 00:43:45,958
Fellow who looks into every pot. He
told me you camped near me last night.

485
00:43:46,031 --> 00:43:48,693
Don't you remember my leavin'
your fire after dark?

486
00:43:48,767 --> 00:43:50,701
I don't recall.

487
00:43:55,474 --> 00:43:58,875
Yesterday,
two hunters trailed her.

488
00:43:58,944 --> 00:44:01,606
Said she left a trail
as easy to follow as a bear's.

489
00:44:01,680 --> 00:44:07,118
When dark came, they were not more
than a hundred yards from my camp.

490
00:44:09,788 --> 00:44:11,722
She's tryin' to find you,
it looks like.

491
00:44:11,790 --> 00:44:14,691
She must've come near yours.

492
00:44:14,760 --> 00:44:16,694
You think she came
to steal somethin'?

493
00:44:16,762 --> 00:44:18,696
She's not a thief.

494
00:44:26,438 --> 00:44:28,872
I would have sworn!

495
00:44:28,941 --> 00:44:32,843
That farmer--
whatever his name was--

496
00:44:32,911 --> 00:44:35,675
he said there were footprints.

497
00:44:37,516 --> 00:44:39,450
What does a slave eat, anyway?

498
00:44:39,518 --> 00:44:41,452
Milk?

499
00:44:43,956 --> 00:44:46,356
What do you think she eats?

500
00:44:46,425 --> 00:44:48,723
She eats anything!

501
00:44:48,794 --> 00:44:51,319
What does that matter?
I want to find her!

502
00:44:51,396 --> 00:44:55,389
And she was near here!
Near me, near you-- last night!

503
00:44:55,467 --> 00:44:57,992
Just wonderin' what she might
want to steal from me, that's all.

504
00:44:58,070 --> 00:45:00,004
She's not a thief!

505
00:45:00,072 --> 00:45:02,131
Don't shout at me, Olaf.

506
00:45:12,017 --> 00:45:14,212
 

507
00:45:14,286 --> 00:45:17,312
I did expect to find her.

508
00:45:17,389 --> 00:45:21,086
I was certain it was you.
I told people up ahead it was you.

509
00:45:21,159 --> 00:45:24,595
Though I never used your name,
whatever it is.
What'd you say?

510
00:45:24,663 --> 00:45:28,258
She's with a man with a full-blood
cow tied by a rope to his cart.

511
00:45:28,333 --> 00:45:31,097
I don't much like you
usin' me, Olaf.

512
00:45:33,572 --> 00:45:35,506
 

513
00:45:44,716 --> 00:45:46,650
 

514
00:45:48,920 --> 00:45:51,445
 

515
00:45:51,523 --> 00:45:53,548
Most everybody's
gonna stop you now.

516
00:45:57,863 --> 00:46:01,060
I can disappear
when I get that scared.

517
00:46:15,080 --> 00:46:17,014
Wait till I get back.

518
00:46:25,390 --> 00:46:27,517
 

519
00:47:25,450 --> 00:47:28,385
§  

520
00:47:35,961 --> 00:47:38,657
§  

521
00:47:47,906 --> 00:47:49,840
Where's your mama live?

522
00:47:53,311 --> 00:47:55,245
Why, in his house.

523
00:47:56,314 --> 00:47:58,248
You his daughter?

524
00:47:59,317 --> 00:48:01,285
How's that?

525
00:48:01,353 --> 00:48:05,153
You Olaf's daughter?

526
00:48:11,229 --> 00:48:13,322
Uh-huh.

527
